Steps: 
Install Git, VS Code

Go to: Spring Initializer
* Project: Maven (Ensures your dependencies route to your D:\GlobalCaches\MavenRepository folder).
* Language: Java
* Spring Boot: Select the latest stable version (e.g., 3.x.x). Do not select versions with (SNAPSHOT) as they are unstable developer builds.
* Project Metadata: Leave as default or name it com.bdapps.paidapp.
* Packaging: Jar
* Java: Select 17 or 21 (matching whatever version of Azul Zulu JDK FX you unzipped into D:\JavaEnv\jdk-azulyfx).
* Dependencies (Click "Add Dependencies" or Ctrl + B and search for these three):
1. Spring Web: Gives you the server engine to listen to payment requests.
   2. Spring Security: Necessary to lock features and require user accounts.
   3. MySQL Driver: Connects your backend to your existing local XAMPP MySQL database.

Click Generate (Ctrl + Enter). It will download a lightweight .zip file. Save it directly to D:\JavaApps\, and unzip it there into your project folder.
👉 It downloads a .zip
Extract the zip: 
You’ll get a folder like:
demo/
 ├── src/
 ├── pom.xml
 
Open in VS Code:
File → Open Folder → select demo
🟩 What just happened?
👉 Spring Boot is already included via:
pom.xml
You don’t manually install anything.

🟨 Run the project (important):
In VS Code terminal:
./mvnw spring-boot:run
👉 Then open browser:
http://localhost:8080

🟥 Alternative (VS Code extension):
You can install:
Spring Boot Extension Pack
👉 It lets you generate projects inside VS Code
But honestly:
# 👉 Spring Initializr is simplest of all


Create GitHub repo: Go to GitHub. Click New Repository. Name it (same as your folder)
Upload Java project to GitHub: GitHub will show commands. Use each one at a time:
git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/your-repo.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

Every time you change something:
git add .
git commit -m "describe what you changed. type the exact(particular thing that u changed)"
git push

